[32m│[0m ### detailed_summary                                                         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m Successfully tested the /convert endpoint with a valid external URL          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m (http://example.com). The endpoint fetches the remote content and displays   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m it in the response. The application returned HTTP 200 OK and rendered the    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m fetched HTML content from example.com on the page. The response shows that   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m the application is able to successfully connect to and retrieve content from [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m external URLs, processing them and embedding them in the result div of the   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m HTML response.                                                               [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The output confirms that the /convert endpoint:                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 1. Accepts POST requests with url parameter                                  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 2. Successfully fetches external URLs                                        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 3. Returns HTTP 200 OK (not a redirect like with failed requests)            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 4. Embeds the fetched content in the response HTML                           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m This validates that external URL fetching works as expected, which provides  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m a baseline for comparing against attempts to access internal/local URLs      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m (which fail with "Connection refused" errors and show 302 redirects).        [32m│[0m
